1) Creation of a new file Chordpitchdetection.h 

FFT + Harmonic Product Spectrum (HPS)

After applying a Hann window to reduce spectral leakage, we compute the FFT of the frame to get the magnitude spectrum — essentially a picture of which frequencies are present in the signal and how strong they are.
The problem with a raw FFT on a chord is that you see many peaks (one per string, plus all their harmonics) and no obvious way to know which is the root. HPS solves this by exploiting a fundamental property of musical sounds: every pitched note produces energy at its fundamental frequency and at integer multiples of it (2×, 3×, 4×...). The algorithm downsamples the spectrum by those same integer factors and multiplies all the versions together. At most frequencies, the product stays small because the peaks don't align. But at the true fundamental of the lowest note, the peaks from every harmonic stack land on the same bin simultaneously — the product spikes dramatically there.
Concretely: if the root is at 98 Hz (G2), there will be energy at 98, 196, 294, 392 Hz. Downsampling the spectrum by 2 shifts 196 Hz down to 98 Hz. Downsampling by 3 shifts 294 Hz down to 98 Hz. Multiplying everything together makes 98 Hz win by a large margin over any competing bin.
A parabolic interpolation step then refines the detected bin to sub-bin precision, giving frequency accuracy well below the FFT's natural resolution.
Finally, a 3-frame median filter smooths out occasional frame-to-frame errors, and an attack detector flushes that filter whenever the RMS rises sharply — so chord transitions aren't delayed by stale history from the previous chord.

